{{Infobox scholar | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | name = ʿAbd al‐Wājid | fullname = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Mashhad]], [[Iran]] | death_date = 1434 | death_place = [[Kütahya]], [[Aegean Region]], [[Turkey]] | era = | region = | school_tradition = | main_interests = [[Astronomy]] | notable_ideas = | major_works = | influences = [[Maragheh observatory]], [[Muḥammad ibn Ḥamza al‐Fanārī]], [[Jaghmīnī]], [[Nasir al-Din al-Tusi]], [[Qutb al-Din al-Shirazi]]{{sfn|Topdemir|2007}} | influenced = }}
'''Badr al‐Dīn ʿAbd al‐Wājid (or Wāḥid) ibn Muḥammad ibn Muḥammad al‐Ḥanafī''' (born in [[Mashhad]], [[Iran]] – 1434 [[Kütahya]], [[Turkey]]) was a notable [[Islamic astronomer]] who taught in the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] Demirkapi Madrasa, a school for astronomical observation and instruction that was later renamed to the Wājidiyya Madrasa in his honor.{{sfn|Topdemir|2007}}
In addition to [[Qutb al-Din al-Shirazi]], he contributed to bringing the influence of the [[Maragheh observatory]] to [[Anatolia]].{{sfn|Topdemir|2007}}
== Works ==
* ''Sharḥ al‐Mulakhkhaṣ fī al‐hayʾa'' ("A commentary on the Compendium of Astronomy"), a commentary on [[Jaghmīnī]]'s famous work. Dedicated to Sultan [[Murād II]]. * ''Sharḥ Sī faṣl'', a commentary on [[Ṭūsī]]'s Persian work of astronomy. Translated into Turkish by Ahmed‐i Dāʿī. * ''Maʿālim al‐awqāt wa‐sharḥuhu'', a work in the use of [[astrolabe]] written in verse using 552 couplets. Dedicated to Muḥammad Shāh (d. 1406), the son of [[Muḥammad ibn Ḥamza al‐Fanārī|al‐Fanārī]] (d. 1431).{{sfn|Topdemir|2007}}
